Three agents — a yard spotter who can read inbound containers' attributes and see their intake slots, a logistics planner who holds each container's target bay, and a crane operator who runs the crane from a cab and cannot read container attributes — coordinate over a shared link channel to sort each round's batch of inbound containers into their assigned bays across {{ round_count }} rounds. Containers carry no ID numbers: each is identified only by its visible attributes (colour, size, type, marking). Every character sent on the link channel costs one simulated second against a fixed {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}-second window; if the window is exhausted the round fails.

The spotter knows each container's attributes and the intake slot it sits in, but not its destination. The planner knows each container's attributes and its target bay, but not where it currently sits. The crane operator can move a container from any slot to any slot but is blind to attributes, so it cannot tell the containers apart on its own. To place a container, the spotter's report (which container is in which slot) and the planner's report (which container goes to which bay) must be matched on the container's attributes — and the assignment is drawn fresh every round, so it cannot be memorized.
